%N A387907 a(n) = position of first odd digit of 2^n, starting from left, or 0 if no odd digit exists.
%C A387907 It is conjectured that a(n) is positive for n >= 12. This is sometimes known as the "2048 problem".
%C A387907 The first digit of 2^n follows Benford's law asymptotically (see Raimi reference), so the proportion of n with a(n) = 1 is log10(2*4*6*8*10) - log10(3*5*7*9) ~= 0.6088... .
%H A387907 Michael S. Branicky, <a href="/A387907/b387907.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 0..10000</a>
%H A387907 Ralph A. Raimi, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1080/00029890.1976.11994162">The first digit problem</a>, Amer. Math. Monthly, 83 (1976), 521-538.
%H A387907 Wikipedia, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Benford%27s_law">Benford's law</a>
%F A387907 a(n) = 0 iff 2^n in A068994. - _Michael S. Branicky_, Sep 20 2025
%e A387907 a(6) = 0 because 2^6 = 64 has no odd digits.
%e A387907 a(10) = 1 because the first digit of 2^10 = 1024, from the left, is odd.
%e A387907 a(18) = 4 because the first odd digit of 2^18 = 262144, from the left, is the 4th digit.
%t A387907 a[n_]:=Module[{so=Boole[OddQ/@IntegerDigits[2^n]]},If[Total[so]==0,0,Position[so,1][[1]]]];Array[a,86,0]//Flatten (* _James C. McMahon_, Sep 20 2025 *)
%o A387907 (PARI) a(n) = my(x=select(x->(x%2), digits(2^n), 1)); if (#x, x[1], 0); \\ _Michel Marcus_, Sep 14 2025
